#wideblock[
  
== Test 3

Some people have decided to reduce the number of times they fly every year or to stop flying altogether. Do you think the environmental benefits of this development outweigh the disadvantages for individuals and businesses?]

#作文(timing: 58, words: 253, date: "2025-12-11")[To reduce carbon emission, some environmentally concerned people have decided to limit their flights or even give up flying altogether. While this is laudable to put the environment before one's own expediency, the actual benefits might be minimal. #praise[][观点明确]

Firstly, it's not immediately clear that other means of transportation effectively emit less carbon than airplanes. The extra carbon incurred by driving, for example, in lieu of flying, may collectively surpass by far the amount of #typo[petroline][petrol] saved in the plane's oil tank: a flight will still take off in spite of a few cancellations. Indeed, only a tiny fraction of people will opt out of a flight in reality for environmental reasons, and the net effect may well be more carbon released. #issue[][未提供数据或合理推演]

It's only when flight #issue[reductions reaches][主谓一致错误] a #issue[critical mass][“关键临界规模”概念需要深入解释。] can we start to talk about its environmental benefits, but at what costs? For starters, some long distance travels are only practical by air -- #praise[its timeliness][指代清晰] is essential for global business #issue[travels][应为不可数名词travel]. Even at the individual level, a flight's ease and efficiency is so taken for granted that its absence is enough to put a #typo[top][stop] to a #typo[holidy][holiday] plan. In other words, the cost of a significant reduction in air travel is stalled businesses and #typo[frastrated][frustrated] people that may drastically outweigh the environmental benefits. After all, protecting the environment is a means to produce healthy businesses and happy people.

In summary, the environmental benefits of limited flights are dubious at best, but their practical impact on business and individuals are detrimental.]

